formula_63 is the relocated pole positioned to set the desired cutoff attenuation.

formula_64 is a ripple cutoff pole that has been modified for even order pass bands.

formula_65 is the passband attenuation ripple in dB (.05 dB, 1 dB, etc.)).

formula_66 is the desired passband attenuation at the cutoff frequency in dB (1 dB, 3 dB, 10 dB, etc.)

formula_3 is the number of poles (the order of the filter).

formula_68 is the smallest even order Chebyshev Node

== Type II Chebyshev filters (inverse Chebyshev filters) ==
Also known as inverse Chebyshev filters, the Type II Chebyshev filter type is less common because it does not roll off as fast as Type I, and requires more components. It has no ripple in the passband, but does have equiripple in the stopband. The gain is:

:formula_69

In the stopband, the Chebyshev polynomial oscillates between -1 and 1 so that the gain will oscillate between zero and

:formula_70

and the smallest frequency at which this maximum is attained is the cutoff frequency formula_71. The parameter ε is thus related to the stopband attenuation γ in decibels by:

:formula_72

For a stopband attenuation of 5 dB, ε = 0.6801; for an attenuation of 10 dB, ε = 0.3333. The frequency &quot;f&quot;0 = &quot;ω&quot;0/2&quot;π&quot; is the cutoff frequency. The 3 dB frequency &quot;f&quot;H is related to &quot;f&quot;0 by:

:formula_73

=== Poles and zeroes ===
Assuming that the cutoff frequency is equal to unity, the poles formula_21 of the gain of the Chebyshev filter are the zeroes of the denominator of the gain:

:formula_75

The poles of gain of the type II Chebyshev filter are the inverse of the poles of the type I filter:

